Convenience functions to MO parameters

Source: R/parameter.R
parameter.Rd

The following functions are convenience wrappers to create intensities parameters for the MO distribution and ex_intensities parameters for the exMO distribution.

ex_intensities_constant(d, constant)

intensities_constant(d, constant)

ex_intensities_linear(d, scale)

intensities_linear(d, scale)

ex_intensities_cuadras_auge(d, alpha, beta)

intensities_cuadras_auge(d, alpha, beta)

ex_intensities_poisson(d, lambda, eta)

intensities_poisson(d, lambda, eta)

ex_intensities_alpha_stable(d, alpha)

intensities_alpha_stable(d, alpha)

ex_intensities_exponential(d, lambda)

intensities_exponential(d, lambda)

ex_intensities_gamma(d, a)

intensities_gamma(d, a)

ex_intensities_pareto(d, alpha, x0)

intensities_pareto(d, alpha, x0)

ex_intensities_inverse_gaussian(d, eta)

intensities_inverse_gaussian(d, eta)

Arguments

d

Dimension of the distribution
constant

Rate for global shock, passed to constant parameter for ConstantBernsteinFunction
scale

Rates for individual shocks, passed to scale parameter for LinearBernsteinFunction
alpha

Alpha parameter for Pareto CPP, passed to alpha parameter of ParetoBernsteinFunction
beta

Rate for global shock, passed to constant parameter for ConstantBernsteinFunction
lambda

lambda parameter for Exponential-jump CPP subordinator, passed to lambda parameter of ExponentialBernsteinFunction
eta

eta parameter for the inverse Gaussian BF, passed to eta parameter of InverseGaussianBernsteinFunction
a

Shape parameter for Gamma subordinator, passed to a parameter of GammaBernsteinFunction
x0

Cutoff parameter for Pareto CPP, passed to x0 parameter of ParetoBernsteinFunction

Details

For more information, please read the corresponding documentation for the respective Bernstein function.
